More Notes: PAGE-ICE yields SCCO2 values about two times higher than PAGE09 due to climate and economic updates.

Economy feedbacks demonstrate a manifold increase in the SCCO2 resulting from an empirically derived estimate of partially persistent economic damages. Almost entirely due to higher damages in the Global South. Reported with a conservative multiple.
Including an estimate of interannual temperature variability increases the width of the SCCO2 distribution, with particularly strong effects in the tails and a slight increase in the mean SCCO2.
Estimated SCCO2 exceeds $5000 for some runs impacted by damage persistence in lower-income regions.
SCCO2 remains high unless persistence lowers annually by >2% through adaptation.
Reductions in persistence of at least 3% per year required for SCCO2 less than $600.
Mean increase of $21 (6.5%) due to annual temperature variability.

Based on PAGE09, PAGE-ICE, and PAGE with interannual temperature variability. Distributions shown as boxplots with whiskers at 5th and 95th percentiles. Setting Value to zero as specific number is not mentioned.

Based on PAGE-ICE with growtheffects, and PAGE with both growtheffects and interannual variability. Distributions shown as boxplots with whiskers at 5th and 95th percentiles. Setting Value to zero as specific number is not mentioned.

Impact of variability on projected current damages in 2100 expressed as a percentage of GDP in that year, separately for the three damage modules affected by temperature anomalies (Discontinuity, Market, Non-economic). Distributions are shown as boxplots, so 5th and 95th percentile information can be extracted. Setting Value to zero as specific number is not mentioned.
